<Layout title="Sales Appraisal vs Rental Appraisal: What Brisbane Property Owners Need to Understand 2027 | Daniel Gierach Property" description="A sales appraisal and a rental appraisal measure different things and are provided by different people. Here is what each one tells you, why you often need both, and when to get them." draft={draft}>

<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the difference between a sales appraisal and a rental appraisal in Brisbane?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A sales appraisal is a real estate agent's opinion of what your property would sell for on the current market, based on comparable recent sales. A rental appraisal is a property manager's opinion of what your property would rent for per week, based on comparable recent lettings. They measure different things: one tells you what a buyer will pay today, the other tells you what a tenant will pay per week. Both are typically provided free of charge as part of a listing or management pitch."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do I need a rental appraisal if I am selling my Brisbane property to owner-occupiers?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A rental appraisal adds value even when the likely buyer pool is predominantly owner-occupiers, because some owner-occupier buyers still consider rental income as part of their financial planning. However, the rental appraisal matters most when selling to investors. If your property is likely to attract investor buyers, having a strong rental appraisal from a credible property manager is an important part of your marketing materials because investors use the rental figure to calculate yield."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How do I calculate the gross rental yield on my Brisbane investment property?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Gross rental yield is calculated by dividing the annual rental income by the purchase price, then expressing the result as a percentage. For example, if a Brisbane property sells for $800,000 and achieves $620 per week in rent, the annual rental income is approximately $32,240 (620 x 52). Dividing $32,240 by $800,000 gives a gross yield of approximately 4.0%. This is the gross yield only: it does not account for property management fees, rates, insurance, or maintenance costs."
      }
    }
  ]
}
