      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Sales Appraisal vs Rental Appraisal: What Brisbane Property Owners Need to Understand
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        These two appraisals measure different things and are provided by different people. Understanding what each one tells you, and when to get both, helps you make a more informed decision about whether to sell or hold.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Brisbane property owners weighing up whether to sell or hold an investment property are often told to get an appraisal. What is less often explained is that there are two distinct types of appraisal, each measuring something different and each provided by a different professional. Conflating them, or relying on only one when you need both, leads to incomplete information and sometimes to poor decisions.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a sales appraisal is</h2>
      <p>A sales appraisal, sometimes called a market appraisal or a comparative market analysis, is a real estate agent's opinion of what your property would sell for if listed on the current market. The agent draws on recent sales of comparable properties in the same suburb or surrounding area, assessing similarities in size, condition, configuration, and location to arrive at a likely sale price range.</p>

      <p>A sales appraisal is not a formal valuation. A formal valuation is conducted by a registered property valuer, follows a specific methodology, and produces a documented report that can be relied upon by lenders and courts. A sales appraisal is the agent's professional opinion based on market knowledge and comparable evidence. It is less formal and carries no legal weight, but it is the most practical and accessible tool for understanding current market value. It is typically provided free of charge by selling agents as part of a listing pitch.</p>

      <p>A good sales appraisal will identify the specific comparable sales the agent has used, explain how your property compares to those sales, and give you a realistic price range rather than an aspirational number designed to win your business. The quality of a sales appraisal depends heavily on the depth of the agent's local knowledge and their willingness to give you an honest assessment rather than telling you what you want to hear.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a rental appraisal is</h2>
      <p>A rental appraisal is a property manager's opinion of what your property would achieve in weekly rent if listed on the current rental market. The property manager assesses comparable rental listings and recent lettings of similar properties in the area to arrive at a likely weekly rent range. Like a sales appraisal, it is typically provided free of charge, usually by a property management agency as part of a management pitch.</p>

      <p>A rental appraisal reflects what a tenant will pay per week under the current supply and demand conditions in the rental market. It is distinct from the sales appraisal in that it measures income rather than capital value. A property with a high sales appraisal does not necessarily have a high rental appraisal: the relationship between the two figures determines rental yield, which is a critical metric for investment property decisions.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why Brisbane property owners often need both</h2>
      <p>For an owner-occupier who has decided to sell their primary residence, a rental appraisal may be of limited relevance. But for anyone holding an investment property and weighing up whether to sell or continue renting it out, having both figures is essential. The sales appraisal tells you what you could realise from the sale today. The rental appraisal tells you what income you could generate by continuing to hold the property. Comparing the two allows you to assess the yield you are currently achieving, or could achieve, and weigh it against what the capital proceeds from a sale could generate if invested elsewhere.</p>

      <p>Investment property sellers targeting an investor buyer pool also need a strong rental appraisal as part of their marketing materials. Investors are buying based on yield, and yield is calculated from the rental income relative to the purchase price. A property advertised with a credible rental appraisal from a well-regarded local property manager is a more compelling investment proposition than one with no rental information, because the buyer can immediately assess the income potential without having to do their own research.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to calculate gross rental yield</h2>
      <p>Gross rental yield is calculated by dividing the annual rental income by the purchase price and expressing the result as a percentage. If your property achieves $650 per week in rent and sells for $850,000, the annual rental income is approximately $33,800 (650 multiplied by 52). Dividing $33,800 by $850,000 gives a gross yield of approximately 3.97%, or roughly 4.0%.</p>

      <p>Gross yield is the standard shorthand investors use to compare properties, but it is important to understand that it is gross, not net. Net yield accounts for property management fees (typically 8% to 10% of rental income), rates, insurance, maintenance, and body corporate levies if applicable. After deducting those costs, the net yield on a Brisbane inner-east investment property is typically 1.0% to 1.5% lower than the gross figure. An investor looking at a property offering 4.0% gross yield should expect a net yield closer to 2.5% to 3.0% after costs.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who provides each appraisal</h2>
      <p>A sales appraisal is provided by a licensed real estate sales agent. To be meaningful, it should come from an agent with a genuine track record of recent sales in your suburb and price range. An agent who has sold in your street or building in the past 12 months will have more accurate and relevant comparable data than one who primarily operates in a different area.</p>

      <p>A rental appraisal is typically provided by a property management specialist, which may be a dedicated property management agency or the property management division of a real estate office with a strong rental book in your area. If your property is currently tenanted and managed by an existing property manager, that manager is well-placed to provide a rental appraisal because they already know the building, the tenancy history, and the local rental demand. If the property is not currently rented, seek a rental appraisal from a manager with a demonstrated track record of letting comparable properties in the same suburb.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When to get each appraisal</h2>
      <p>If you are genuinely undecided between selling and continuing to hold, get both appraisals before making a decision. The combination of a current sales appraisal and a current rental appraisal gives you the information you need to run a basic sell-versus-hold analysis: what the property is worth today, what income it can generate if held, and what yield you are earning on the capital tied up in the property. Without both numbers, you are making a decision with incomplete information.</p>

      <p>If you have already decided to sell but are selling to an investor buyer pool, obtain a rental appraisal before listing and include it in your marketing materials. A credible rental appraisal from a local property manager with a strong rental book is a meaningful piece of marketing collateral for a property targeting investor buyers. It makes the financial case for the purchase concrete rather than requiring the buyer to estimate the rental income themselves.</p>

